This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it proposes a novel architecture for learning and extracting invariant representations from event streams originating from neuromorphic vision sensors. The paper also explores the applicability of the framework on real-world tasks by using the learned network for object recognition. 

The paper also involves the concepts of sparsity and temporal slowness, which are commonly used in neural network models (cs.NE). 

The proposed model achieves higher classification accuracy compared to other state-of-the-art event-based processing methods, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. 

Finally, the paper's focus on using the learned feature detectors for object recognition suggests that it may also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category, as object recognition is an important task in robotics.
